abstract: In “Friendship: The Evolution, Biology, and Extraordinary Power of Life’s Fundamental Bond,” Lydia Denworth explores the growing, cross-species science of friendships — how they work and why.

abstract: Ezra Klein’s “Why We’re Polarized” seeks to explain what has changed in our electoral politics and why our differences are so hard to overcome.

headline_main: Why America’s Political Divisions Will Only Get Worse

abstract: The former national security adviser shared his unease with the attorney general, who cited his own worries about the president’s conversations with the leaders of Turkey and China.
snippet: The former national security adviser shared his unease with the attorney general, who cited his own worries about the president’s conversations with the leaders of Turkey and China.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — John R. Bolton, the former national security adviser, privately told Attorney General William P. Barr last year that he had concerns that President Trump was effectively granting personal favors to the autocratic leaders of Turkey and China, according to an unpublished manuscript by Mr. Bolton.

headline_main: Wuhan Coronavirus, Impeachment, Kobe Bryant: Your Tuesday Briefing

abstract: Debates, graphs, writing exercises, art projects and more for teaching and learning about football’s biggest game.
snippet: Debates, graphs, writing exercises, art projects and more for teaching and learning about football’s biggest game.
lead_paragraph: How can you make this week’s Super Bowl relevant to your curriculum? Whether debating football-related controversies, making predictions, analyzing ads, writing descriptions, understanding data and statistics, or learning about head trauma, we have ideas for using The Times and The Learning Network to help you do just that.
